{{other ships|Italian ship Cristoforo Colombo}} {|{{Infobox ship begin}} {{Infobox ship image |Ship image=Cristoforo Colombo Italian Royal Navy ship.jpg |Ship caption= ''Cristoforo Colombo'' in Italian service }} {{Infobox ship career |Hide header= |Ship country= |Ship flag={{shipboxflag|Kingdom of Italy}} |Ship name= ''[[Christopher Columbus|Cristoforo Colombo]]'' |Ship namesake= |Ship ordered= |Ship builder= |Ship laid down= April 15, 1926 |Ship launched= April 4, 1928 |Ship acquired= |Ship commissioned= 1 July 1928 |Ship decommissioned= |Ship in service= |Ship out of service= |Ship struck= |Ship reinstated= |Ship honours= |Ship fate=Ceded to the Soviet Union as war reparation, March 1949 |Ship status= |Ship notes= }} {{Infobox ship career |Hide header=title |Ship country= |Ship flag={{shipboxflag|Soviet Union|naval}} |Ship name= ''Dunay'' |Ship acquired= 1949 |Ship commissioned= |Ship decommissioned= |Ship in service= |Ship out of service= |Ship struck= 1959 |Ship reinstated= |Ship honours= |Ship fate= Destroyed by fire in 1963 |Ship status= |Ship notes= }} {{Infobox ship characteristics |Hide header= |Header caption= |Ship class= |Ship displacement= {{convert|4.146|t|LT|0|lk=out|abbr=on}} standard |Ship length= {{convert|100.5|m|ftin|abbr=on}}{{Citation needed|date=January 2014}} |Ship beam= {{convert|15.5|m|ftin|abbr=on}}{{Citation needed|date=January 2014}} |Ship height= |Ship draught= {{convert|7|m|ftin|abbr=on}} |Ship propulsion=sail |Ship speed=10 knots |Ship range= |Ship complement=400 |Ship sensors= |Ship EW= |Ship armament= |Ship aircraft= |Ship aircraft facilities= |Ship notes= }} |} The '''''Dunay''''' was a tall ship serving with the [[Soviet Navy]], first launched as the '''''Cristoforo Colombo''''', laid at the Castellammare yards on April 15, 1926. It was destroyed in a fire in 1963.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ac-support.europe.umuc.edu/~jmatthew/naples/criscol.html|title=The Strange Fate of the Cristoforo Colombo|publisher=Around Naples Encyclopedia|accessdate=10 August 2011}}</ref>
==History== In 1925, the [[Regia Marina]] ordered two school ships to a design by General Lieutenant Francesco Rotundi of the Italian Navy Engineering Corps, inspired by the style of large late 18th century 74-cannon [[ship of the line|ships of the line]]. The first, the ''Cristoforo Colombo'', was put into service in 1928 and was used by the Italian Navy until 1943. After [[World War II]], the ship was handed over to the Soviet Union as part of the [[war reparation]]s demanded by the [[Paris Peace Treaties, 1947|1947 Paris Peace Treaty]], and was decommissioned in 1959.
The second ship was the ''[[Italian training ship Amerigo Vespucci|Amerigo Vespucci]]'', launched in 1931 and is still in service.
